<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Scenario...<br>
Two parents are discussing discipline for their child. The child has broken something that belonged to the<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->... <br>
<br>
Parents who have not discussed how to raise children and discussed things like whether to baptise, religious/non-religious upbringing, daycare, parental roles and the dreaded corporal vs. time out punishment should be flogged themselves!! How valuabe the item is, moreover is not really that relevant to the punishment except to get across to a child that some things should be handled with extra care and matter more to the owner when you are careless and lose or break them---assuming the perpetrator is older than 4 years!!<br>
<br>
That said--parents should seek information if they don't have it already from professionals and even friends and family they respect and be willing to reconsider their own ideas. I went through the very thing with a biting phase recently and was told to bite my son back, slap him harder, yell really loud etc. and my dh and I talked, and talked and talked and did our best meanwhile (like 24 hours worth at first just to try to stop the biting before he got kicked out of daycare). We both learned alot and compromised on things, actually taking an approach neither of us had originally thought of or wanted!! Go figure. With hitting kids I can't see much compromise, but perhaps they could at least agree to do some quick learning (tell kid you'll sleep on it then run to computer/bookstore/elder/sister/mom/daycare lady) and implement Plan United Parental Front together. <br>
<br>
P.S. I hate when one parent does all the punishing and the other says &quot;wait til you &lt;insert parent&gt; gets home&quot;. What a crappy role for the spanker/grounder.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Scenario...<br>
A married couple go car shopping. The wife wants to get a minivan, no kids yet but planning on a family. The husband wants a two seater sports car, the kids won't be for two or three years, plenty of time to trade it in later for the minivan. How do you respect both people, give equal consideration to each persons wants/needs? Buy both cars, or buy none?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Wow--again personal experience. Firstly, no shopping without extensive research including Consumer Reports, blue book and safety records--regardless of whether or not children will be riding. Then talk, talk, talk to decide together. Perhaps a bigger car but not van or sporty, truck version of SUV or a motorcycle for dad on the side and cheaper van for mom now...there are hundreds of options that can make both feel good. <br>
<br>
Sometimes you do give in on some things too in marriage, but certainly not because of what's between your legs or because one of you was &quot;meant to be the head&quot;. I laid down veeeery firm rules when dh and I returned from a relo that I would only move if it could be done before ds was born but really didn't want a 2 story. I didn't care about it that terribly much, but it's really bad for me now with degenerative arthritis setting in on my knees... but I knew he loved this house and decided early on that if he could come through on getting the house, moving in, fixing up the old one (by himself no less) that where we went and what the house looked like wasn't my main thing. The bigger issue for me was the timing, so I feel I got that and the big issue for him was the 3 car garage with &quot;man room&quot; added on back, pre-done landscaping and 2 stories with all the things he liked. We both won, we both gave in on some things. Had nothing to do with gender.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I would assume all of the people here have to submit in some way or another to there spouse.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
No. You are confusing submission with compromise. I compromise on things at work but don't consider it &quot;submitting&quot; to the other team members. The difference is the differing gender roles, assumptions about women's god-given (or not given) abilities and final decision maker. The man's role is not equal, it is the CEO...sure he takes input and respects his underlings, but he has the power.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But he is the head of my house and I respect him.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Some wish to live in a kingdom as a servant to a ruler they adore. I wish to live in a democracy with no head, but a congress of leadership compromising, talking, discussing and working it out on equal ground. <br>
