My dh and I are first and foremost best friends.  When it comes to decisions we are equals.  We discuss our thoughts and ideas and then come to a compromise.  <br>
<br>
I do expect him to take the lead in things like Family prayer, family council and family home evening and other spiritual matters.  At times though I have been the more committed one in our family and so I shared my ideas and sugestions but allowed him to grow by backing off of the decision making process leaving it in his hands.  This says I trust you and support you and I want you to be successful.<br>
<br>
The man is not above the woman.  Even in the creation story, Eve is called a help meet, not a help mate.    She was taken out of his side, to stand beside him.  We have equal but different charachteristics. Physically, emotionally and spiritually we are two halves of a whole.  The perfect match.<br>
<br>
There is a joke in the LDS church that the husband may preside, but the wife usually conducts.  In other words that old saying that behind every great man there is a great woman.<br>
<br>
I think the concern lies when people assume that because a woman is wife and mother that she cant have any other role.  Which is definitly not our doctrine (admittedly there are jerky LDS men out there who think this way)  As LDS women we are strongly encouraged to get an education and the brethern recognize that having a sahm in every home is not feasible.  Whether financially not a possiblity or for the health and well being of the woman and family.  <br>
<br>
Personal example - I was a sahm for two years.  I was perusing the want ads one day, dh was thinking of changing jobs.  I ran across the job I have now.  I felt a distinct prompting that I should look at this job and that it was a perfect fit for me and my skills.  I looked it up and everything I had ever loved in my previous jobs was wrapped up into this postion and it was part time with benefits making what I had been making before staying home.  I had not planned on going back to work until my dd was  in school but I applied for the job and went through the interviewing process knowing that I would get the job.  <br>
<br>
When I started working it became very apparent to me that I had missed the professional half of myself more than I had realized.  It wasnt a financial need, but an emotional need that the Lord knew I had. <br>
<br>
No one should ever judge the way another couple chooses to divy out responsibilities and roles. <br>
